–Overleden","1512–1589":"1512–1589","1516–Female":"1516–Overleden","July 1561":"juli 1561","27 September 1562":"27 september 1562","9 December 1564":"9 december 1564","21 July 1560":"21 juli 1560","1561":"1561","1572":"1572","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1589":"1589","1600":"1600","1512":"1512","1587":"1587","1564":"1564","1520":"1520","1585":"1585","1562":"1562","2 March 1604":"2 maart 1604","1607":"1607","1616":"1616","1605":"1605","1538":"1538","1549":"1549","1516":"1516","1604":"1604","Nuthurst, Sussex, England":"Nuthurst, Sussex, England","Sawbridgeworth, Hertfordshire, England":"Sawbridgeworth, Hertfordshire, England"},"en":{"1538–2 March 1604":"1538–2 March 1604","1538–1604":"1538–1604","–1572":"–1572","1520–1605":"1520–1605","1561–1616":"1561–1616","1562–1607":"1562–1607","1564–Male":"1564–Deceased","1512–1589":"1512–1589","1516–Female":"1516–Deceased","July 1561":"July 1561","27 September 1562":"27 September 1562","9 December 1564":"9 December 1564","21 July 1560":"21 July 1560","1561":"1561","1572":"1572","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1589":"1589","1600":"1600","1512":"1512","1587":"1587","1564":"1564","1520":"1520","1585":"1585","1562":"1562","2 March 1604":"2 March 1604","1607":"1607","1616":"1616","1605":"1605","1538":"1538","1549":"1549","1516":"1516","1604":"1604","Nuthurst, Sussex, England":"Nuthurst, Sussex, England","Sawbridgeworth, Hertfordshire, England":"Sawbridgeworth, Hertfordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Jane","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a feminine form of   John  , from the Old French form <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Since the 17th century it has proved the most popular of the feminine forms of <i>John</i>, ahead of   Joan   and   Jean .  It now also commonly occurs as the second element in combinations such as <i>Sarah-Jane</i>. In Britain it is still one of the most frequent of all girls' names. It is not a royal name, but was borne by the tragic  Lady Jane Grey  (  1537–54 ), who was unwillingly proclaimed queen in  1553 , deposed nine days later, and executed the following year. Seventy years earlier, the name had come into prominence as that of  Jane Shore , mistress of  King Edward IV  and subsequently of  Thomas Grey , 1st Marquess of Dorset, Lady Jane's grandfather. Jane Shore's tribulations in  1483  at the hands of  Richard III , Edward's brother and successor, became the subject of popular ballads and plays, which may well have increased the currency of the name in the 16th century. A 19th-century influence was its use as the name of the central character in  Charlotte Brontë's  novel Jane Eyre (  1847 ). From  1932 to 1959  it was used as the name of a cheerful and scantily clad beauty whose adventures were chronicled in a strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror. It is also borne by the American film stars  Jane Russell  (  1921–2011 ) and  Jane Fonda  (  b. 1937 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Jayne","meanings":["Elaborated spelling of   Jane  , a form popularized no doubt by the American actress  Jayne Mansfield  (  Vera Jayne Palmer ,  1933–67 ) and British ice-dancer  Jayne Torvill  (  b. 1957 )."]},{"name":"Jaine","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Jane ."]},{"name":"Jain","meanings":["Originally a feminine form of   John  , from the Old French form <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Since the 17th century it has proved the most popular of the feminine forms of <i>John</i>, ahead of   Joan   and   Jean .  It now also commonly occurs as the second element in combinations such as <i>Sarah-Jane</i>. In Britain it is still one of the most frequent of all girls' names. It is not a royal name, but was borne by the tragic  Lady Jane Grey  (  1537–54 ), who was unwillingly proclaimed queen in  1553 , deposed nine days later, and executed the following year. Seventy years earlier, the name had come into prominence as that of  Jane Shore , mistress of  King Edward IV  and subsequently of  Thomas Grey , 1st Marquess of Dorset, Lady Jane's grandfather. Jane Shore's tribulations in  1483  at the hands of  Richard III , Edward's brother and successor, became the subject of popular ballads and plays, which may well have increased the currency of the name in the 16th century. A 19th-century influence was its use as the name of the central character in  Charlotte Brontë's  novel Jane Eyre (  1847 ). From  1932 to 1959  it was used as the name of a cheerful and scantily clad beauty whose adventures were chronicled in a strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror. It is also borne by the American film stars  Jane Russell  (  1921–2011 ) and  Jane Fonda  (  b. 1937 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":11,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":20,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705205,"age":31,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705207,"age":47,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705208,"age":49,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705210,"age":62,"year":"1600","julianDay":2305448,"title":"The Honourable East India Company","description":"The Honourable East India Company, a British joint-stock company, was established in 1600 for trade in the Indian Ocean region. At its height, the British East India Company had a private army which was twice the size of the British Army, ruled large sections of India, and revenues in the millions.","url":"https://www.historic-uk.com/HistoryUK/HistoryofEngland/The-East-India-Company/","urlTitle":"Historic UK - The East India Company","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Jane Plowewrighte was born in 1538, in Sawbridgeworth, Hertfordshire, England, her father, Plowright, was 27 and her mother, Mrs. Plowright, was 23. She married William Cramphorne on 21 July 1560, in Sawbridgeworth, Hertfordshire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. She died on 2 March 1604, in her hometown, at the age of 66."},"et":{"1538–2 March 1604":"1538–2. märts 1604","1538–1604":"1538–1604","–1572":"–1572","1520–1605":"1520–1605","1561–1616":"1561–1616","1562–1607":"1562–1607","1564–Male":"1564–Surnud","1512–1589":"1512–1589","1516–Female":"1516–Surnud","July 1561":"juuli 1561","27 September 1562":"27. september 1562","9 December 1564":"9. detsember 1564","21 July 1560":"21. juuli 1560"